  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-hemolysis-not-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CPB hemolysis worst-case identification, MRL 2) concludes with a Not-accepted decision based on three factors that fail to meet their required credibility levels: (1) Discretization error: Required level 3, achieved level 2. The mesh refinement study demonstrates a GCI of 9.8% for the primary hemolysis QoI at the production mesh resolution, exceeding the 5% threshold required at level 3. Spatial discretization error is not sufficiently bounded to support confident hemolysis predictions, particularly in the high-shear impeller tip region where hemolysis is most sensitive to mesh resolution. (2) Model form: Required level 3, achieved level 2. The hemolysis power-law model (Zhang et al. 2011) has not been validated against an independent model form, and the k-omega SST turbulence closure exhibits a 14% velocity discrepancy relative to PIV measurements in the impeller passage. The absence of a model-form uncertainty quantification study — comparing at least two candidate hemolysis models across the operating envelope — is a material gap at MRL 2 for a High decision-consequence COU. (3) Model inputs: Required level 3, achieved level 2. Formal uncertainty propagation for dominant input parameters (blood viscosity model, inlet velocity profile, blade angle tolerances) was not performed. The inlet boundary condition mismatch between the parabolic profile assumed in simulation and the plug-flow condition present in experiments is unquantified and may contribute systematically to the observed 18.4% MAE in NIH predictions. Taken together, these three deficiencies are not independent: discretization error, model-form uncertainty, and input uncertainty collectively prevent reliable attribution of the 18.4% NIH prediction error to any single source, and the combined uncertainty budget cannot be shown to be acceptable for a High-consequence decision. The Not-accepted decision is therefore fully justified by the structured evidence. Remediation pathway: (a) refine mesh to achieve GCI < 5% for NIH; (b) perform comparative model-form study with Giersiepen and Taskin hemolysis models; (c) conduct formal uncertainty propagation covering blood viscosity model, inlet profile, and geometric tolerances; (d) resubmit for credibility review upon completion of all three remediation activities.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
